d seem to be applicable at the Delivery Point Support for the argument that the surcharge is not a tax under the contracts 1  The CPUC refers to it as a rate increase 2  It was not imposed by a governmental body such as a state county or municipality 3  When first implemented all proceeds went to the utilities 4  It appears that a portion of the proceeds may continue to go to the utilities Support for the argument that the surcharge is a tax under the contracts 1  Since the frozen tariff remains in place it is disingenuous to refer to it as a rate increase 2  It now appears that the proceeds will go to a governmental entity the DWR 3  The definition of taxes under the contract is broad and includes surcharges of all types 4  To the extent the 01 surcharge is to pay for generation for bundled customers those on direct access receive if anything only an indirect benefit which is similar in effect to a tax and not to a rate increase 
